\f1\b\fs26 Wednesday, November 10, 1762
\f0\b0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f1\fs26  Even with the leaves falling off the trees, Mortimer Reece thought America was beautiful. At least the middle colonies part of America. New England had its beauties, more in the inhabitants than the scenery. The Carolinas were too hot and sandy. The Quakers managed to pick the best part of America. The further away from Philadelphia they rode, the more he enjoyed the scenery.\
The road widened as they entered the town. The afternoon sun just started to dip below the tops of the trees. Sharpsburg, he thought they named it. As they rode through, it looked quaint enough. Grey stone buildings in the Georgian style. They were not going anywhere. He chuckled when he saw the wooden fort. He pointed it out to Dorian Mabbott. \'93Sharpsburg has permanent buildings but temporary fortifications. They should be glad hostilities are at an end.\'94\
\'93Shippensburg, sir.\'94\
\'93What?\'94\
\'93We are in Shippensburg, sir. Named for Chief Justice Shippen.\'94 Dorian\'92s tone was respectful.\
\'93Quite right. Shippens-burg.\'94 He muttered its name a few times under his breath. \'93Still, he does have a beautiful wife.\'94\
\'93Who, sir?\'94\
\'93His Honorable Judge Shippen.\'94\
\'93Yes, sir.\'94\
\'93Do you see the church?\'94\
\'93Not yet, sir. I doubt he\'92s in one. They\'92re Presbyterians out in the country. He was trained in the Puritan tradition.\'94\
Mortimer chuckled at that. 
\f0\fs24 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f1\i\fs26 Puritans are a tradition? Hardly.
\f0\i0\fs24 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f1\fs26  \'93Damned separatists. The Church of England is the only civil church. God save the King.\'94\
His men repeated in unison, \'93God save the king.\'94\
\
\'93Still, I\'92ll buy you a pint if he\'92s not found in a church.\'94\
They rode until they came to the tavern. \'93Widow Piper\'92s Tavern. Handsome structure, that. Such clean lines. I wonder who built it?\'94 He shifted in his saddle. It had been a long ride. \'93Come on, let\'92s give it some business.\'94\
He and his men dismounted and tied their horses. Mortimer paused a few more minutes to study the shape of the building. For an American tavern, it was not terribly large. Its size was more like the alehouses in London.\
The ten of them entered the tavern. Describe interior.\

