The common area was just large enough for his entourage. A woman, probably Widow Piper, worked the fire by the hearth.\
\'93Good evening, madam.\'94\
She looked up. \'93How can I be of service?\'94 The Scottish burr was distinct, unsoftened by her time in America.\
\'93If you have lodging,\'94 pointing his hat at his men, \'93we will be staying the night.\'94\
She smiled. \'93Aye. No boarders today.\'94\
\'93Splendid. We\'92ve just arrived from.\'94 He paused an turned to Dorian.\
\'93Harrisburg, sir.\'94\
\'93Yes. Quite. Harrisburg. Hard journey. We are famished.\'94\
\'93Well, you\'92re in luck. We have a meat pie, hasty pudding with bacon, oatmeal porridge, a dish of eggs and beer. Should be ready in an hour.\'94\
\'93No ale, perhaps?\'94 Mortimer said.\
\'93Aye, ale beer.\'94\
After a pint, Mortimer\'92s men took the horses to the nearby stable while Moritmer and Dorian remained. They were on their second pint. The prices were lower than Mortimer would have expected. It was a decent ale, even if too malty for his palette.\
\
\'93Mrs. Piper. Have you recently had a visitor?\'94\
\'93This is a tavern, sir. With all the travel between Philadelphia and the wilderness, we usually have several visitors. Usually redcoats or trappers. It starts to slow down about this season.\'94\
\'93Anyone by the name of Ephraim Biggs?\'94 Dorian jumped in.\
Mortimer felt a little exasperated. Dorian was younger, always in haste.\
\'93No Ephraim Biggs. There is a Jeffry Biggs here in town.\'94\
Mortimer sat up a little. \'93Oh?\'94\
\'93Aye. He lives just on the other side of the fort.\'94\
Dorian continued, \'93has he been here long?\'94\
\'93He brought his family here a couple years ago. Once the indian troubles started to quiet down a bit.\'94\
\'93Pastor?\'94\
\'93Oh, no. Worse. He\'92s a lawyer.\'94\
\'93There does not seem to be much calling for the law out here.\'94 Mortimer injected.\
\'93You\'92d be surprised. He works for Judge Shippen, who owns all the land around us. Once the war is over, they\'92ll be selling plots of land. Mr. Biggs will be handling the surveys and sales. He usually comes in every morning for a beer and Indian pudding with the missus being with child.\'94\
\
* * *\
\
The next morning, Mortimer and Dorian sat over breakfast and waited. Mrs. Piper described Jeffry to them, so they were prepared. They did not wait long. A somewhat tall man with reddish-brown hair came into the tavern.\
\'93Jeffry!\'94\
The man reflexively looked their way.\
\'93Join us.\'94\
\'93I\'92m sorry. Who are you?\'94\
\'93I\'92m Captain Reece, and this is Ensign Mabbott. You are Jeffry Biggs, land broker?\'94\
That seemed to put Jeffry at ease. He hesitated for a moment before joining them at the table. Mortimer observed his mannerisms as an odd mix of gentleman and commoner. Jeffry was pretending at being one, probably a gentleman.\
There was serving bowl of Indian pudding. Mortimer pushed it toward Jeffry. He offered a spare bowl and wooden spoon to Jeffry, who took it from him. Jeffry filled his bowl. Dorian set a mug of ale at Jeffry\'92s place. The three ate together, trading small talk for most of the meal.\
\'93Thank you, gentlemen, for that wonderful breakfast. Piper has excellent pudding. I am afraid we are not offering plots for sale quite yet. Once a peace treaty is signed, perhaps.\'94\
\'93I imaging in time Shippensburg will be a thriving city. Handsome countryside. We are not here for that. Have you heard from your brother Ephraim?\'94\
Jeffry paused for a moment. His facial expression changed almost imperceptibly. It was enough for Mortimer to judge that Ephraim was here recently. \'93No, I haven\'92t. He should be in New Haven.\'94 Mortimer thought Jeffry did not sound like he expected Ephraim to actually be in New Haven.\
\'93Should be, but he is not. He left New Haven some months ago, and I\'92m tasked with finding him.\'94\
\'93Is he in some sort of trouble?\'94\
Mortimer paused. As a younger brother, he would want nothing better but for his older brother to disappear. Then he would have title and would not be traipsing over the back side of America, to Mortimer\'92s brother\'92s delight. Would Jeffry protect his brother or not? Mortimer decided confronting him with a hard statement would yield a worthwhile reaction. \'93I\'92m afraid he is. Ephraim Biggs murdered an English officer last June in New Haven. I\'92ve been dispatched to find him for execution.\'94\
Dorian started to react when Mortimer cut him off with a glare. It denied him the chance to see Jeffry\'92s reaction.\
\'93But...No. I don\'92t believe it. Jeffy isn\'92t the murderous sort.\'94\
Mortimer let a silent pause work for him. Colonial Colonel Whiting hated playing All Fours against Mortimer because of his ability to read the other players. He tried those tactics here. When Jeffry looked down, he gave a glance and wink to Dorian. \'93Tried and convicted, I\'92m afraid. He managed to escape the jail soon after. Ensign Mabbott and I have been in pursuit ever since. He gave us a slip in Philadelphia, but we hear rumor that he headed this way. Pray, when did you last see your brother?\'94\
\'93Not since he went to Yale.\'94\
It was a lie that Mortimer read easily. He opted to change tact. \'93Well, he must not have come this way, then. We were convinced he would seek refuge with family. Ensign, you may have been right. He went to Baltimore.\'94 He noticed Jeffry relax his shoulders, though the look of shock on his face remained. \'93What amazed me that a Puritan ministerial student would be capable of murder with his bare hands. How is it that you became an attorney and he went a different path?\'94\
\'93We weren\'92t born into wealth, if that\'92s what you mean. Our forefathers were smiths. Our grandfather came over after Queen Anne\'92s War. Our father did well enough to send us to college so we could advance the family\'92s position.\'94\
\'93So you worked in the smithy as lads? That would explain Ephraim\'92s ability to crush a man\'92s throat.\'94 Mentally, Mortimer moved the Biggs down several social pegs. Commoners pretending to be elitists. That was the mode in America, with men thinking they can climb some social ladder and forget their places. It was different for aristocrats. They already had their place. All that remained was jockeying for position.\
The meal ended abruptly there. The interrogation stole whatever appetite Jeffry still had. He thanked them and left.\
\'93What was that about?\'94 Dorian said.\
\'93About the conviction? I had to know whether Jeffry knew about the murder. I dressed it up a bit.\'94 He set back in his chair. He steepled his hands together, and tapped his upper lip. \'93His brother went through here, but failed to tell his brother why. I doubt they are very close. Jeffry is quite a few years older. Did you notice anything else?\'94\
\'93They are smiths.\'94\
\'93Quite. Ephraim will not conceal himself as a pastor. Too obvious, and not as much call for that out here. Scottish Presbyterians and Purtain Separatists.\'94\
\'93You suppose he reverted to smithing?\'94\
\'93It makes sense. Either that or he\'92s fled the country and gone south.\'94 Ensign Mabbott had not been in America for long. Mortimer decided to size him up a bit. \'93What course of action do you propose?\'94\
\'93Well, we are close to Indian country. There are not too many places that could take a smith. He could have fled south, but his resources would only take him too far. I\'92ll wager a pint that he is in a nearby town working as a smith.\'94\
\'93How do you propose we find out?\'94\
\'93Divide our forces. Winter is fast approaching. But, if we send the men out a few days in any direction, we should figure out if he is in the area or has passed through.\'94\

